00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:07.770
"Radical Markets, Uprooting
Capitalism and Democracy

00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:09.600
for a Just Society."

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:10.521
Take it away.

00:01:10.521 --> 00:01:11.479
GLEN WEYL: Thanks, Hal.

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:17.110
And thanks everyone for coming.

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:25.240
So this work is the culmination
of many years of careful policy

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:30.790
design research with Eric
Posner, but in the 10 minutes

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:32.860
I have to introduce
it, I think, rather

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:35.200
than going into the details
of all of the proposals

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:37.210
that we have, it's
best to just give you

00:01:37.210 --> 00:01:39.957
a flavor of the
sort of broad idea

00:01:39.957 --> 00:01:41.290
that we're trying to get across.

00:01:41.290 --> 00:01:43.630
And I think that
that's best conveyed

00:01:43.630 --> 00:01:45.320
by a thought experiment.

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:47.080
So I want you to,
for the moment,

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:49.420
suspend your practical
considerations

00:01:49.420 --> 00:01:52.120
and come with me on a
journey of imagination,

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:56.230
to a fictive city that I'm
going to call Marketopia.

00:01:56.230 --> 00:01:59.200
Marketopia is a
bit like Zootopia,

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:02.170
except rather than
being defined by having

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:05.700
a diverse group of mammals
that inhabit it, instead

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:09.740
Marketopia is defined
by the fact that all

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:17.050
the major private
property in Marketopia--

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:22.470
let's put aside personal effects
like heirlooms, and pets,

00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:23.600
and so forth--

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:25.510
but all the land,
and the houses,

00:02:25.510 --> 00:02:28.780
and the airplanes, and
so forth, is continually

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:33.520
up for auction to the
highest bidder, in a manner

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:36.010
somewhat similar to the
way that search terms

00:02:36.010 --> 00:02:40.010
are for Google advertisements.

00:02:40.010 --> 00:02:43.810
So basically,
whoever is currently

00:02:43.810 --> 00:02:47.440
the highest bidder on
one of these pieces

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:50.440
of private property controls
it for the time being,

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:54.910
by making a rental payment
continually into a central pot

00:02:54.910 --> 00:02:57.520
until someone else comes
along, and beats their price,

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:00.640
and takes over that
rental payment for control

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:02.860
of that asset.

00:03:02.860 --> 00:03:08.740
And that's not just true of
private property in Marketopia.

00:03:08.740 --> 00:03:11.620
In fact, many things that we
would usually consider to be

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:15.790
determined by collective
decision-making processes,

00:03:15.790 --> 00:03:25.370
like the location of parks and
the politicians that govern

00:03:25.370 --> 00:03:30.400
Marketopia, what sort of schools
they have, and what they teach,

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:31.460
and so forth--

00:03:31.460 --> 00:03:33.490
these are also determined
by an auction process,

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:37.930
though rather than auctioning
them to the highest bidder,

00:03:37.930 --> 00:03:40.030
we add up the total
willingness of everyone

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:41.800
to pay for different
alternatives,

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:44.620
and we implement the one that
people are willing in total

00:03:44.620 --> 00:03:46.750
to pay the most for.

00:03:46.750 --> 00:03:49.030
And all the money that's
raised by these auctions

00:03:49.030 --> 00:03:53.230
is continually returned to
all the citizens of Marketopia

00:03:53.230 --> 00:03:56.560
in equal shares, as
a social dividend,

00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:59.530
or you might call it a
universal basic income.

00:03:59.530 --> 00:04:03.130
Much as in Norway and
Alaska, when they auction off

00:04:03.130 --> 00:04:06.160
oil rights, they
return the revenue

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:08.940
that they raise to the citizens.

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:11.640
Now when you hear this
idea of Marketopia,

00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:15.210
it might sound like sort
of the most extreme version

00:04:15.210 --> 00:04:16.950
of a free market
that you can imagine.

00:04:16.950 --> 00:04:20.700
It's much crazier than
anything that, say,

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:25.620
Adam Smith could have
imagined, because it makes

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:31.430
you realize that even though
we live in a market society,

00:04:31.430 --> 00:04:34.960
most things are not
available for liquid purchase

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:37.240
at any given point in time.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.610
Most of the land on
the Google campus--

00:04:40.610 --> 00:04:42.640
most of the stock
of Google, in fact--

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:45.610
not just the marginal units
of stock that are currently

00:04:45.610 --> 00:04:48.010
on bid, but most of the
stock that all of you hold--

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:49.426
these aren't things
you could just

00:04:49.426 --> 00:04:52.600
go out and buy at some
price at any point in time.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:56.680
Those are instead controlled
by often-wealthy concentrated

00:04:56.680 --> 00:05:00.460
interests, and if you wanted to
grab control of those assets,

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:03.580
you'd have to enter into
a long and drawn out

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:05.170
process of bargaining,
and probably

00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:08.140
pay many times what the person
would be willing to accept,

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.770
because they'd get wind that
you'd want to buy that thing.

00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:16.960
And so Marketopia is a far more
extreme, complete free market

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:20.650
than any society in history.

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:26.400
And that might lead you to
think, OK, so in Marketopia,

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:28.690
the wealthy are going to
dominate everything, right?

00:05:28.690 --> 00:05:30.440
The wealthy are going
to be able to outbid

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:32.000
the prices that anyone
else is going to pay.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:33.350
They're going to take
control of assets

00:05:33.350 --> 00:05:35.270
and they're going to
use that to dominate

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:37.130
everyone else in society.

00:05:37.130 --> 00:05:38.660
But then you have
to ask yourself,

00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:42.010
what do you mean by the wealthy?

00:05:42.010 --> 00:05:43.970
Well, a wealthy
person is someone

00:05:43.970 --> 00:05:49.340
who has lots of assets, like
stocks, and bonds, and houses,

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:52.310
and land, and businesses.

00:05:52.310 --> 00:05:54.950
But in Marketopia, there
is no private ownership

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:55.820
of those things.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:57.620
All of those things
are continually

00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:00.270
auctioned for the
public benefit.

00:06:00.270 --> 00:06:06.950
In fact, Marketopia is actually
the most extreme version

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:10.430
of the sort of common ownership
advocated by people like Karl

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:11.660
Marx that you can imagine.

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:14.090
Much more extreme than
forms of socialism

00:06:14.090 --> 00:06:16.520
that actually existed,
which ended up

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:20.720
in the control of those
assets by a concentrated

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:24.110
bureaucratic elite, that often
ended up tyrannizing over

00:06:24.110 --> 00:06:26.360
the rest of the
population even more

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:31.210
intensely than the capitalists
that they claimed to replace.

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:32.770
In Marketopia, on
the other hand,

00:06:32.770 --> 00:06:36.890
there is true common ownership,
because by construction,

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:40.610
all the value of all assets
flow equally to all citizens,

00:06:40.610 --> 00:06:44.870
and by construction, every
citizen has an equal right

00:06:44.870 --> 00:06:49.090
to compete for
control of assets.

00:06:49.090 --> 00:06:51.160
This might seem like
a paradox, especially

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:54.430
to those of us who grew up in
the Cold War and post-Cold War

00:06:54.430 --> 00:06:55.240
periods.

00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:59.800
How can the most extreme form of
common ownership, of communism,

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:03.310
go along with the most
extreme form of a free market?

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:05.630
Well, while that might
seem like a paradox,

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:10.300
it's actually a
crucial part of what

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:14.410
was the central tradition
in a field called

00:07:14.410 --> 00:07:19.400
political economy, that
gave birth to economics,

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:23.830
political science, sociology,
and many other fields

00:07:23.830 --> 00:07:26.620
during the late 19th century.

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:31.090
And this idea called competitive
common ownership was especially

00:07:31.090 --> 00:07:35.000
associated with the
work of this guy here.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.980
And I wonder if
anyone recognizes him.

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:37.480
Who is that?

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:38.890
AUDIENCE: Henry George.

00:07:38.890 --> 00:07:39.790
GLEN WEYL: Wow!

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:42.340
This is the first time
anyone has actually

00:07:42.340 --> 00:07:44.176
managed to identify him.

00:07:44.176 --> 00:07:46.120
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:50.820
GLEN WEYL: Well, I'm glad
I came to the right place.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:53.550
So you could probably repeat
the following things for me,

00:07:53.550 --> 00:07:58.830
but Henry George was
the best-selling author

00:07:58.830 --> 00:08:00.840
in the English language,
other than the Bible,

00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:02.460
for about 30 years.

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:04.380
His book, "Progress
and Poverty,"

00:08:04.380 --> 00:08:07.380
was the namesake of the
Progressive movement

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:08.400
in the United States.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:12.404
He helped inspire the Chinese
nationalist revolution

00:08:12.404 --> 00:08:13.320
and many other things.

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:16.260
He was an enormously
influential person,

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:21.120
and yet his ideas are largely
forgotten in the post-Cold War

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:22.320
era.

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:27.159
And the goal of this book is
to revive the tradition that

00:08:27.159 --> 00:08:28.950
was represented by
Henry George and others,

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:32.669
like Leon Walras, many of the
founders of modern economics,

00:08:32.669 --> 00:08:36.570
who believed that free
markets, true free markets,

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:41.385
and true socialism
went hand-in-hand.

00:08:41.385 --> 00:08:44.327
To argue that, while these ideas
were forgotten in mainstream

00:08:44.327 --> 00:08:46.410
culture, they continued
to be developed in a field

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:51.030
called mechanism design, which
won lots of Nobel prizes,

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:56.190
but was largely applied to
things like auctioning off

00:08:56.190 --> 00:09:00.780
search words at companies
like Google and Facebook,

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:03.810
rather than to the big problems
of social organization.

00:09:03.810 --> 00:09:06.810
And to show that we can,
based on this tradition,

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:09.090
have a new way of
organizing society

00:09:09.090 --> 00:09:12.270
to address our most
pressing problems.

00:09:12.270 --> 00:09:15.270
And the way that we do
that is by developing five

00:09:15.270 --> 00:09:17.550
detailed, practical
policy proposals,

00:09:17.550 --> 00:09:23.730
building off of this spirit,
that instantiate this idea

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:26.790
and address, we think, some
of the most pressing problems

00:09:26.790 --> 00:09:32.550
of inequality, slow
growth, and social conflict

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:34.736
over political issues.

00:09:34.736 --> 00:09:35.735
So what are those ideas?

00:09:38.630 --> 00:09:40.840
The first, which is
most closely associated

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:42.610
with this auction
I was describing,

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:46.600
is the common ownership
self-assessed tax, in which

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:50.020
every owner of significant
private property

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:54.970
would self-assess the value of
that property at some value,

00:09:54.970 --> 00:09:57.940
stand willing to sell the
property at that value,

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:01.040
and then pay a tax on
that self-assessed value.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:03.760
So this would be a way of
implementing the auction

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:05.860
that I was describing,
without taking

00:10:05.860 --> 00:10:08.320
all ownership into the public,
so that people would still

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:10.090
have some incentive
to make investments.

00:10:16.870 --> 00:10:21.920
So people would still have an
incentive to make investments.

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:24.850
And at the same time,
all assets would

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:27.070
be liquidly available
for turnover

00:10:27.070 --> 00:10:29.590
to a better potential use.

00:10:29.590 --> 00:10:32.380
The second idea is
quadratic voting.

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:35.050
This is a system of
sort of auctioning,

00:10:35.050 --> 00:10:37.030
but for collective
decision making

00:10:37.030 --> 00:10:39.610
that would protect
minorities by allowing

00:10:39.610 --> 00:10:42.910
them to express the greater
strength of their interest

00:10:42.910 --> 00:10:46.079
in given issues
compared to majorities.

00:10:46.079 --> 00:10:48.370
The way that it would work,
is that every citizen would

00:10:48.370 --> 00:10:50.980
be endowed with a
budget of voice credits

00:10:50.980 --> 00:10:55.270
that they could spend on
different politicians or issues

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:58.760
in a referenda that
are important to them,

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:00.760
and they could put more
votes on the issues that

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:02.510
were more important
to them, but according

00:11:02.510 --> 00:11:05.680
to a very particular rule,
which is that the cost in voice

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:08.200
credits of influence
on any given issue

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:10.450
would be the square
of the number of votes

00:11:10.450 --> 00:11:13.960
that you buy on that issue.

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:17.290
Third, we propose a new
system of migration,

00:11:17.290 --> 00:11:19.960
in which immigration
would benefit,

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:23.020
rather than just the
immigrants and the capitalists

00:11:23.020 --> 00:11:26.320
in the wealthy countries,
instead it would

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:30.700
it would benefit all
citizens, because rather

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:32.800
than large corporations
or governments

00:11:32.800 --> 00:11:35.500
determining who was
admitted to the country,

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:39.130
instead individual citizens
would have the right

00:11:39.130 --> 00:11:42.760
to sponsor visas for
migrants and to negotiate--

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:45.760
subject to some protections--
a share of the benefits

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:51.640
that the migrants received from
migrating to wealthy countries.

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:54.430
So that would allow for
massively increased migration,

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:56.650
but with the broad
support of the working

00:11:56.650 --> 00:11:59.650
classes of wealthy countries.

00:11:59.650 --> 00:12:04.150
Fourth, we argue that
antitrust policy is

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:06.730
an incredibly powerful
tool for maintaining

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:08.620
a competitive and
dynamic economy,

00:12:08.620 --> 00:12:10.450
but that it has been
almost completely

00:12:10.450 --> 00:12:14.770
unenforced in the two most
important areas in which market

00:12:14.770 --> 00:12:17.020
power is accumulating
in our economy,

00:12:17.020 --> 00:12:20.440
and therefore we've
been ignoring about 80%,

00:12:20.440 --> 00:12:23.410
or maybe even 90%, of
the potential benefits

00:12:23.410 --> 00:12:24.340
of antitrust.

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:28.270
Those two areas are that, first
of all, institutional investors

00:12:28.270 --> 00:12:31.840
like Vanguard, State Street,
BlackRock, et cetera,

00:12:31.840 --> 00:12:35.410
now control about a third of
the total corporate economy,

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:39.400
and are the four or five
largest shareholders of almost

00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:43.690
every major corporation
straight across industries,

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:47.141
Google and Microsoft,
American Airlines and Delta.

00:12:47.141 --> 00:12:48.640
And therefore, they
have no interest

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:51.070
in seeing these companies
compete with each other.

00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:55.600
And we've seen rising
prices in close correlation

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:59.740
to the growing power
of these companies.

00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:02.565
That's sort of the most
comprehensive market power

00:13:02.565 --> 00:13:03.940
that's ever existed,
because it's

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:08.810
coordinated almost the entirety
of the corporate economy.

00:13:08.810 --> 00:13:11.500
Another area that's been
almost completely neglected

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:14.350
by antitrust policy
has been the power

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:17.140
that companies have
over workers, rather

00:13:17.140 --> 00:13:19.130
than over consumers.

00:13:19.130 --> 00:13:24.010
Because if you think about a
typical consumption decision

00:13:24.010 --> 00:13:26.770
you make, like what
type of water to drink,

00:13:26.770 --> 00:13:29.620
there's probably 10 or 15
reasonable alternatives

00:13:29.620 --> 00:13:30.250
you have.

00:13:30.250 --> 00:13:32.740
Whereas if you think about a
job, what's your next best job

00:13:32.740 --> 00:13:34.450
rather than working
at Google, it's

00:13:34.450 --> 00:13:36.700
probably a way worse option.

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:39.130
And maybe you have
one other option,

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:46.100
but it's much less competitive
than is a typical product

00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:46.600
market.

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:50.800
And yet there's literally never
been an antitrust merger case

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:52.690
that blocked a merger
because of the way

00:13:52.690 --> 00:13:58.060
it reduced options for
employment for workers.

00:13:58.060 --> 00:14:02.470
And finally, we argue that
the individual contributions

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:05.080
that people make to
the digital economy

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:08.920
should be treated as
essentially labor,

00:14:08.920 --> 00:14:11.590
and that there should be
a labor movement of people

00:14:11.590 --> 00:14:16.000
who are contributing that
data, to organize, to demand

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.540
a fair share of the value
created by their data

00:14:19.540 --> 00:14:23.050
from companies like Google,
Facebook, and Microsoft.

00:14:23.050 --> 00:14:25.540
Because increasingly,
people are worried

00:14:25.540 --> 00:14:30.010
about artificial intelligence
taking people's jobs,

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:34.180
but as all of us here know, all
that artificial intelligence

00:14:34.180 --> 00:14:36.160
is trained based on human data.

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:41.500
And it's, in fact, a lot more
like some sort of broadcasting

00:14:41.500 --> 00:14:44.260
of our data than it is
just brilliant engineers

00:14:44.260 --> 00:14:47.450
programming computers to
go and take people's jobs.

00:14:47.450 --> 00:14:50.260
And so, if people
were more fairly

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:52.630
compensated for their
data, the digital economy

00:14:52.630 --> 00:14:55.690
would be a source of economic
opportunity for people,

00:14:55.690 --> 00:14:59.230
rather than an economic threat.

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:01.630
Now all these ideas
are quite radical.

00:15:01.630 --> 00:15:03.790
All of them would require
fundamental changes

00:15:03.790 --> 00:15:05.140
to our social institutions.

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:09.160
And while for each of these
chapters, we have concrete,

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:12.880
near-term, non-controversial
steps we can make in that

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:17.150
direction, we also know that
as a broad social philosophy,

00:15:17.150 --> 00:15:20.090
no one would seriously consider
this if we weren't in a moment

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:23.960
of social crisis that
really, deeply required new

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:26.840
out-of-the-box thinking like
this to avoid potentially

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:28.160
catastrophic outcomes.

00:15:28.160 --> 00:15:30.920
But I truly do believe we
are in a moment like that,

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:32.790
for three reasons.

00:15:32.790 --> 00:15:36.770
One is growing inequality.

00:15:36.770 --> 00:15:42.800
On the left here, we see a graph
of the share of national income

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:46.340
accruing to the top 1% and
the top 0.1% of the income

00:15:46.340 --> 00:15:52.280
distribution, which has
doubled since the 1970s.

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:55.790
And at the same time, we've
seen a dramatic reduction

00:15:55.790 --> 00:15:59.690
in the share of income accruing,
not just to lower income

00:15:59.690 --> 00:16:02.250
workers, but to all
workers in total.

00:16:02.250 --> 00:16:04.370
So the share of income
being paid out to labor,

00:16:04.370 --> 00:16:09.060
as opposed to capital, has
fallen by 10% over this period.

00:16:09.060 --> 00:16:13.160
Now you might think as, say,
Ronald Reagan or Margaret

00:16:13.160 --> 00:16:16.310
Thatcher would have
argued, that that might

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:19.100
be worth it if that's the
price of a more dynamic, more

00:16:19.100 --> 00:16:21.870
competitive, more
innovative economy.

00:16:21.870 --> 00:16:25.640
But at the same time that we've
seen this declining share going

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:29.300
to labor, we've seen
an increasing power

00:16:29.300 --> 00:16:33.500
of corporations to
exert monopoly power.

00:16:33.500 --> 00:16:35.930
That is represented by
this orange line here.

00:16:35.930 --> 00:16:38.540
I've taken the markup
that firms charge--

00:16:38.540 --> 00:16:40.730
that is how much above
their marginal cost

00:16:40.730 --> 00:16:42.710
they charge-- and I've
flipped it around,

00:16:42.710 --> 00:16:45.050
so you can see how
closely it parallels

00:16:45.050 --> 00:16:46.790
the decline in labor incomes.

00:16:46.790 --> 00:16:49.010
So that strongly
suggests that, far

00:16:49.010 --> 00:16:51.110
from us getting a more
competitive economy

00:16:51.110 --> 00:16:55.610
by deregulating, cutting taxes,
and relaxing antitrust policy,

00:16:55.610 --> 00:16:59.090
we've actually seen an
increasing growth of market

00:16:59.090 --> 00:17:05.930
power that is actually reducing
growth rates in the economy,

00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:08.099
as represented in
this graph here.

00:17:08.099 --> 00:17:11.480
So what this shows
is growth rates

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:14.359
in different
wealthy countries in

00:17:14.359 --> 00:17:16.280
the immediate post-war
period, and then

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:18.050
various periods thereafter.

00:17:18.050 --> 00:17:22.099
And the period of the
last several decades

00:17:22.099 --> 00:17:25.819
has had growth rates that
are, in the United States

00:17:25.819 --> 00:17:28.850
about half, and in many
other wealthy countries

00:17:28.850 --> 00:17:32.510
about a tenth, of what they
were in the immediate post-war

00:17:32.510 --> 00:17:34.550
period.

00:17:34.550 --> 00:17:38.720
This combination of stagnation
with growing inequality,

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:43.640
I think, has largely discredited
existing economic ideologies,

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:46.250
as coming out of
Reagan and Thatcher,

00:17:46.250 --> 00:17:49.640
in the same way that the
combination of stagnation

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:52.430
and inflation during
the 1970s discredited

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:55.940
the previous
Keynesian orthodoxy.

00:17:55.940 --> 00:18:00.020
And this stagnant
quality, as we label it,

00:18:00.020 --> 00:18:05.150
and the discrediting of
existing economic ideologies

00:18:05.150 --> 00:18:10.710
has also led to rising political
discontent and conflict.

00:18:10.710 --> 00:18:15.840
Together with the fact that, I
think, political institutions--

00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:20.270
not just economic technocracy,
but political technocracy--

00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:23.010
is increasingly being
viewed as illegitimate,

00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:25.550
there's growing conflicts
between minorities

00:18:25.550 --> 00:18:29.600
and majorities, whether
over immigration,

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:33.830
ethnoracial conflict,
or over, say, things

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:36.140
like gun ownership,
religious minorities.

00:18:36.140 --> 00:18:39.380
And yet the way that wealthy
countries have increasingly

00:18:39.380 --> 00:18:45.260
resolved these issues has
been through the judiciary,

00:18:45.260 --> 00:18:47.840
or through supranational
institutions,

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:49.580
in the case of the
European Union,

00:18:49.580 --> 00:18:52.100
that lack of the
democratic legitimacy

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:55.880
needed for countries to
come to some reasonable way

00:18:55.880 --> 00:18:57.080
of resolving this.

00:18:57.080 --> 00:19:01.310
So there's an increasing feeling
that the economic policies

00:19:01.310 --> 00:19:03.350
and the way that we
resolve political disputes

00:19:03.350 --> 00:19:05.900
are illegitimate,
and that's leading

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:09.290
to the rise of populist
leaders, whether on the right,

00:19:09.290 --> 00:19:13.880
like Trump or Brexit
movement, or on the left,

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:18.140
like Jeremy Corbyn in
the United Kingdom.

00:19:18.140 --> 00:19:21.440
Given all this, I
think we increasingly

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:24.710
feel like the only
path out is these sort

00:19:24.710 --> 00:19:26.390
of reactionary
populist movements

00:19:26.390 --> 00:19:28.380
that don't really
offer an answer.

00:19:28.380 --> 00:19:29.990
And so we feel
the responsibility

00:19:29.990 --> 00:19:32.150
at this moment to
try to put forward

00:19:32.150 --> 00:19:34.550
an alternative,
progressive path that

00:19:34.550 --> 00:19:37.390
can harness the powers
of market and technology,

00:19:37.390 --> 00:19:42.800
but to try to make a more equal,
prosperous, and politically

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:44.510
co-operative society.

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:48.440
And I hope that
you'll open your minds

00:19:48.440 --> 00:19:52.910
to these radical possibilities,
given what we're facing.

00:19:52.910 --> 00:19:55.080
And I'm looking forward to
chatting with all of you

00:19:55.080 --> 00:19:57.792
and with Hal about it.

00:19:57.792 --> 00:19:59.000
HAL VARIAN: All right, great.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:02.879
Very interesting talk, and
let me raise a few objections

00:20:02.879 --> 00:20:03.920
here and there, and see--

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:06.240
because I know that's
your favorite pastime,

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:08.330
is responding to
these objections.

00:20:08.330 --> 00:20:10.940
You know, they say
a cynic believes

00:20:10.940 --> 00:20:15.910
that everything has a price, but
an economist knows it's true.

00:20:15.910 --> 00:20:19.780
So an interesting angle
there on that division--

00:20:19.780 --> 00:20:24.730
this dividing things up, but
then letting people trade--

00:20:24.730 --> 00:20:27.025
what do you do about ability?

00:20:27.025 --> 00:20:30.700
Ability Is very tricky, because
suppose you're a great singer.

00:20:30.700 --> 00:20:34.030
I love to hear you sing, but
it's very tiring for you.

00:20:34.030 --> 00:20:35.080
You don't want to do it.

00:20:35.080 --> 00:20:39.740
Can I outbid you, and
say yes, I bid him.

00:20:39.740 --> 00:20:41.816
He wants to have a
quiet evening at home,

00:20:41.816 --> 00:20:43.190
but I've got this
money I'm going

00:20:43.190 --> 00:20:44.440
to pay him to go out and sing.

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:46.660
GLEN WEYL: That's
a great question.

00:20:46.660 --> 00:20:49.330
We tackle that in the
conclusion of the book.

00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:54.100
For the main part of the book,
we only allow for capital

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:55.400
to be allocated in this way.

00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:57.610
And we think that, at least
in our present society,

00:20:57.610 --> 00:21:00.610
that could address
much of the inequality,

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:03.210
though not all of the
inequality, that we face.

00:21:03.210 --> 00:21:05.800
So we calculate that
with our reforms,

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:08.410
you could get down below
the levels of inequality

00:21:08.410 --> 00:21:12.070
in the 1970s, and significantly
better than in Sweden

00:21:12.070 --> 00:21:12.940
at present.

00:21:12.940 --> 00:21:16.660
But obviously, there would then
be a shift towards inequalities

00:21:16.660 --> 00:21:19.330
that are driven more by
ability, and away from those

00:21:19.330 --> 00:21:22.480
driven by wealth,
And those would

00:21:22.480 --> 00:21:24.370
have to be addressed
by future reforms.

00:21:24.370 --> 00:21:26.350
And we speculate
in the direction

00:21:26.350 --> 00:21:30.970
that you're describing, Hal,
but we don't have a proposal

00:21:30.970 --> 00:21:34.627
that we're happy with actually
putting forward on that.

00:21:34.627 --> 00:21:36.210
HAL VARIAN: Let me
suggest an article.

00:21:36.210 --> 00:21:37.690
it was something I wrote.

00:21:37.690 --> 00:21:40.487
It was my thesis actually
which was on fair division.

00:21:40.487 --> 00:21:42.070
GLEN WEYL: I know
that work very well.

00:21:42.070 --> 00:21:43.250
HAL VARIAN: OK,
well, then you know.

00:21:43.250 --> 00:21:44.750
Because there were
a couple of ideas

00:21:44.750 --> 00:21:46.840
there about how you might
deal with this issue

00:21:46.840 --> 00:21:49.210
of either redefining
what would be fair

00:21:49.210 --> 00:21:52.360
when there's differences
in ability, or, in fact,

00:21:52.360 --> 00:21:55.000
going the very radical
plan of actually,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.745
I could outbid you to
sing and you'd do it.

00:21:57.745 --> 00:22:00.370
GLEN WEYL: Yeah, so I'm actually
very sympathetic to that idea,

00:22:00.370 --> 00:22:02.330
but for a bunch of
practical reasons

00:22:02.330 --> 00:22:03.840
we talk about in
the conclusion, we

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:06.340
don't think we have a proposal
that actually makes sense.

00:22:06.340 --> 00:22:08.650
But at the philosophical
level, you'll

00:22:08.650 --> 00:22:12.797
recognize your own writing in
what we say about that issue.

00:22:12.797 --> 00:22:14.380
HAL VARIAN: And it's
also interesting,

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:16.120
because there is a
practical example.

00:22:16.120 --> 00:22:17.590
There were apprenticeships.

00:22:17.590 --> 00:22:20.210
So what happened in America--

00:22:20.210 --> 00:22:22.850
I mean before there was
a United States, in fact,

00:22:22.850 --> 00:22:25.480
back in the
pre-revolution days--

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:29.526
you could bring an immigrant in,
and the quid pro quo was they

00:22:29.526 --> 00:22:31.150
worked for you for
seven years, and you

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:32.770
would teach them a trade.

00:22:32.770 --> 00:22:35.800
And so this was viewed
as a very successful way

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:38.551
to provide education,
and skills, and so on.

00:22:38.551 --> 00:22:40.300
GLEN WEYL: I wouldn't
say that too loudly,

00:22:40.300 --> 00:22:42.940
because on the internet, when
we certainly weren't advocating

00:22:42.940 --> 00:22:45.010
indentured servitude,
but we just

00:22:45.010 --> 00:22:47.560
talked about our immigration
system, which is not indentured

00:22:47.560 --> 00:22:52.430
servitude, we got the most crazy
reaction from social media.

00:22:52.430 --> 00:22:54.530
So it's a sensitive subject.

00:22:54.530 --> 00:22:55.780
HAL VARIAN: Yes, yes, I agree.

00:22:55.780 --> 00:22:57.090
And it's also illegal, so--

00:22:57.090 --> 00:22:57.715
GLEN WEYL: Yes.

00:23:00.390 --> 00:23:02.140
HAL VARIAN: The
self-assessed tax.

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:03.220
That was kind of fun.

00:23:03.220 --> 00:23:08.270
I first heard this idea from
Dick Zeckhauser many years ago.

00:23:08.270 --> 00:23:10.950
And he claims that
the Greeks used this

00:23:10.950 --> 00:23:12.172
for assessing to antiquities.

00:23:12.172 --> 00:23:13.630
GLEN WEYL: Yeah,
we talked about it

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:15.372
in chapter one in some detail.

00:23:15.372 --> 00:23:17.830
HAL VARIAN: And in fact, we
did something very much like it

00:23:17.830 --> 00:23:19.660
for the top-level
domain names, when

00:23:19.660 --> 00:23:22.900
we had this top-level
domain name auction.

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:25.690
So Microsoft and
Google, for example,

00:23:25.690 --> 00:23:31.570
both might one .doc as a TLD,
and the way it was resolved is

00:23:31.570 --> 00:23:33.220
you each write down your price.

00:23:33.220 --> 00:23:37.240
The high bidder gets it
and pays the other bidder

00:23:37.240 --> 00:23:39.640
the price that it bid.

00:23:39.640 --> 00:23:42.280
So it's a kind of
interesting mechanism.

00:23:42.280 --> 00:23:45.339
It's not, of course, perfect.

00:23:45.339 --> 00:23:47.130
Any economist could
shoot some holes in it,

00:23:47.130 --> 00:23:49.046
but it seemed to work
pretty well in practice.

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:54.010
Data as labor.

00:23:54.010 --> 00:23:56.280
Well, we do that now.

00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:58.360
We pay labellers of data.

00:23:58.360 --> 00:24:02.560
We have just donated
9 million images

00:24:02.560 --> 00:24:04.360
to the Open Image project.

00:24:04.360 --> 00:24:07.120
We paid lots of people
around the world

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:10.460
to label that data
with the contents.

00:24:10.460 --> 00:24:13.660
We did the same thing,
4.5 million YouTube videos

00:24:13.660 --> 00:24:16.750
which we had people
label, and that

00:24:16.750 --> 00:24:20.500
goes into the video project.

00:24:20.500 --> 00:24:23.450
Consumer panels like Nielsen,
that's around all the time.

00:24:23.450 --> 00:24:25.390
So there is a market
for getting people

00:24:25.390 --> 00:24:31.880
to provide data labeling or
data of one sort or another.

00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:34.060
So it's not unreasonably--

00:24:34.060 --> 00:24:35.950
I mean, it's a pretty
big market, really.

00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:37.783
GLEN WEYL: Yeah, I think
that the problem is

00:24:37.783 --> 00:24:39.400
that the vast majority
of data we get,

00:24:39.400 --> 00:24:41.470
we collect from
people who aren't

00:24:41.470 --> 00:24:44.500
aware of the productivity
roles that it ends up playing.

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:47.860
And trying to engage
those people more

00:24:47.860 --> 00:24:50.380
and paying them a bit
more for those people

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:53.219
who are in context, who can
provide additional value.

00:24:53.219 --> 00:24:54.760
And in fact, Google
does a little bit

00:24:54.760 --> 00:24:59.020
of that with the local
hosts and so forth.

00:24:59.020 --> 00:25:01.510
But I think trying to make
people more broadly aware

00:25:01.510 --> 00:25:04.780
of that, and trying to create
a structure where they would

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:08.050
get direct compensation
for improving

00:25:08.050 --> 00:25:09.610
the quality of the
data they provide,

00:25:09.610 --> 00:25:11.859
and be aware of the payments
they were getting for all

00:25:11.859 --> 00:25:14.550
of their data, would
in the medium-term

00:25:14.550 --> 00:25:18.060
create the
opportunity for people

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:25.050
to build greater human
capital, really, and contribute

00:25:25.050 --> 00:25:26.080
more online.

00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:28.080
HAL VARIAN: Well, there
is this question of what

00:25:28.080 --> 00:25:29.246
the payment would look like.

00:25:29.246 --> 00:25:31.650
If you take Facebook
as an example--

00:25:31.650 --> 00:25:34.050
because I think you've
mentioned this--

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:37.350
Facebook had net
earnings of $10 billion,

00:25:37.350 --> 00:25:39.910
and they claim there
are 2 billion users.

00:25:39.910 --> 00:25:43.390
And that means $5.00
a year per user.

00:25:43.390 --> 00:25:45.520
And Google has similar
numbers, of course.

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:47.970
So these work out
to pennies per day,

00:25:47.970 --> 00:25:50.760
in terms of the
compensation for information

00:25:50.760 --> 00:25:51.900
that people are providing.

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:53.550
And I would argue--

00:25:53.550 --> 00:25:55.674
I certainly believe
for Facebook,

00:25:55.674 --> 00:25:57.090
and I certainly
believe for Google

00:25:57.090 --> 00:26:01.200
and also Facebook, of
course-- a lot of this data

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:03.160
is used to improve the product.

00:26:03.160 --> 00:26:04.680
So people are
benefiting from it.

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:07.344
It's benefiting as a public
good, not as a private good,

00:26:07.344 --> 00:26:08.760
but they get their
private benefit

00:26:08.760 --> 00:26:09.884
from using better products.

00:26:09.884 --> 00:26:11.130
GLEN WEYL: Absolutely.

00:26:11.130 --> 00:26:14.580
I think that if we had more
targeted direct compensation

00:26:14.580 --> 00:26:19.009
to people, we would get
larger product improvements.

00:26:19.009 --> 00:26:20.550
I would dispute with
you a little bit

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:21.633
about some of the numbers.

00:26:21.633 --> 00:26:24.590
I've done different
calculations than that exactly,

00:26:24.590 --> 00:26:28.470
but yes, at the moment
things are relatively small,

00:26:28.470 --> 00:26:30.090
I think, by any calculation.

00:26:30.090 --> 00:26:34.020
But in a future where
artificial intelligence really

00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:37.050
does come up to take
the role that investors

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:41.610
are pricing into your company
and into my company, it taking.

00:26:41.610 --> 00:26:45.090
I think that if we don't find
a way to directly compensate

00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:47.809
people for the
data contributions

00:26:47.809 --> 00:26:49.350
that they're making,
that are fueling

00:26:49.350 --> 00:26:51.020
those artificial
intelligence, we're

00:26:51.020 --> 00:26:52.978
going to end up with a
lot of what I would call

00:26:52.978 --> 00:26:55.620
fake unemployment, where
people are unemployed,

00:26:55.620 --> 00:26:57.750
but not because they're
not contributing value,

00:26:57.750 --> 00:27:00.180
just because the value
that they are contributing

00:27:00.180 --> 00:27:03.150
isn't being counted
appropriately.

00:27:03.150 --> 00:27:06.300
HAL VARIAN: If you'd look
at the web raters handbook--

00:27:06.300 --> 00:27:08.460
I was just looking at
this a few days ago.

00:27:08.460 --> 00:27:10.590
I know several people
here have looked at this.

