00:27:58.020 --> 00:27:59.730
describing for those labellers.

00:27:59.730 --> 00:28:03.000
They are a little bit sidelined,
and the public image that is

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.269
portrayed is one in
which you don't--

00:28:05.269 --> 00:28:06.060
HAL VARIAN: I know.

00:28:06.060 --> 00:28:07.230
You're very right.

00:28:07.230 --> 00:28:10.314
I mean nobody knows about this,
even though it's easy to check.

00:28:10.314 --> 00:28:10.980
GLEN WEYL: Yeah.

00:28:10.980 --> 00:28:15.750
I think putting that more center
stage and making more people

00:28:15.750 --> 00:28:17.640
feel like they're
participating in it,

00:28:17.640 --> 00:28:21.060
I think, would change the whole
feeling of using the internet,

00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:23.850
in a way that I think would
be productive for our social

00:28:23.850 --> 00:28:25.770
conversation around technology.

00:28:25.770 --> 00:28:28.770
HAL VARIAN: Well, it is
interesting how many people

00:28:28.770 --> 00:28:32.430
write reviews for Amazon,
or for Google, or for Yelp,

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:36.100
because people are volunteering
this information in many cases.

00:28:36.100 --> 00:28:38.040
And I think you
might want to argue

00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:42.540
that, well, the incremental
addition to that free service

00:28:42.540 --> 00:28:44.597
is worth paying for.

00:28:44.597 --> 00:28:45.930
And maybe it is, maybe it isn't.

00:28:45.930 --> 00:28:47.730
Depends on how much
you're getting people

00:28:47.730 --> 00:28:51.060
to contribute generously
of their time,

00:28:51.060 --> 00:28:53.050
in terms of doing
these evaluations.

00:28:53.050 --> 00:28:54.465
GLEN WEYL: Yeah,
well, that's a--

00:28:54.465 --> 00:28:55.340
HAL VARIAN: Might be.

00:28:55.340 --> 00:28:56.490
It's an empirical matter.

00:28:56.490 --> 00:28:59.550
All right, I'm going to ask one
more question, and I apologize.

00:28:59.550 --> 00:29:00.990
This is slightly technical.

00:29:00.990 --> 00:29:06.909
Your chart on the inference
labor share and the markup,

00:29:06.909 --> 00:29:08.700
I've actually been
working on that problem.

00:29:08.700 --> 00:29:10.490
This is a paper by
Eeckhout and De Loecker

00:29:10.490 --> 00:29:11.370
that you're referring to.

00:29:11.370 --> 00:29:12.690
GLEN WEYL: Yeah, yeah, exactly.

00:29:12.690 --> 00:29:14.490
HAL VARIAN: And
it's a little funny,

00:29:14.490 --> 00:29:21.580
because remember, markup is
the price over marginal cost.

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:24.750
So the markup can go up
either by price going up

00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:26.940
or by marginal cost going down.

00:29:26.940 --> 00:29:28.970
And of course, we
think cost going down,

00:29:28.970 --> 00:29:30.090
gee, that's a good thing.

00:29:30.090 --> 00:29:32.260
Price going up,
that's a bad thing.

00:29:32.260 --> 00:29:34.140
But of course by making--

00:29:34.140 --> 00:29:37.190
by moving around these two
things you can change the--

00:29:37.190 --> 00:29:40.540
level the ratio of
price to marginal cost.

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:42.150
So in fact, if you
take the formula

00:29:42.150 --> 00:29:45.480
in that paper for
the markup, it's

00:29:45.480 --> 00:29:47.670
also a formula
for marginal cost.

00:29:47.670 --> 00:29:49.382
Just re-arrange the algorithm.

00:29:49.382 --> 00:29:51.090
And if you go out and
do the calculation,

00:29:51.090 --> 00:29:53.370
look at the same data-- or
the same sorts of data--

00:29:53.370 --> 00:29:56.790
that they look at, you see
costs going way, way down.

00:29:56.790 --> 00:29:59.520
You also see-- one last point--

00:29:59.520 --> 00:30:01.770
you also see prices going down.

00:30:01.770 --> 00:30:03.360
And the question
is, what's happening

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:05.550
is the marginal cost
is going down even

00:30:05.550 --> 00:30:09.960
faster than the prices are going
down, so the gap is going up.

00:30:09.960 --> 00:30:12.090
GLEN WEYL: Marginal costs
fell dramatically as well

00:30:12.090 --> 00:30:14.940
during the post-war period.

00:30:14.940 --> 00:30:18.060
And in fact, even more
dramatically, the productivity

00:30:18.060 --> 00:30:19.440
went up more quickly.

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:21.914
My view is not everything
has been terrible

00:30:21.914 --> 00:30:22.830
in the last few years.

00:30:22.830 --> 00:30:25.150
That's not the point.

00:30:25.150 --> 00:30:28.300
The point is that, if we don't
have social institutions that

00:30:28.300 --> 00:30:29.940
reform and restrain
market power,

00:30:29.940 --> 00:30:32.640
that keep up with the
progress of technology,

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:35.490
we'll fail to realize the
potential that we can have,

00:30:35.490 --> 00:30:37.680
which requires
constantly breaking up

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:40.890
the sources of rigidity that
enter the economy as technology

00:30:40.890 --> 00:30:41.670
advances.

00:30:41.670 --> 00:30:43.680
And I think we did
that more effectively

00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:46.440
in the immediate post-war period
along certain dimensions--

00:30:46.440 --> 00:30:48.420
though not all
dimensions-- than we've

00:30:48.420 --> 00:30:50.100
managed to do it since then.

00:30:50.100 --> 00:30:53.310
So my argument is not everything
has just gotten worse.

00:30:53.310 --> 00:30:54.009
Of course not.

00:30:54.009 --> 00:30:56.550
We wouldn't have had economic
growth if that hadn't happened.

00:30:56.550 --> 00:30:58.710
But that we haven't
managed to keep up

00:30:58.710 --> 00:31:01.110
in the innovation of
our social institutions

00:31:01.110 --> 00:31:04.050
with the innovation that we've
had on the technological side.

00:31:04.050 --> 00:31:07.500
HAL VARIAN: So let me make one
other objection to the Eeckhout

00:31:07.500 --> 00:31:09.090
De Loecker work.

00:31:09.090 --> 00:31:13.350
Because I don't dispute
anything that you just said.

00:31:13.350 --> 00:31:17.190
But if you look at that, the
surprising thing from other

00:31:17.190 --> 00:31:20.610
contributors is, the same thing
has happened in pretty much

00:31:20.610 --> 00:31:23.410
every industry-- that is,
labor share has gone down--

00:31:23.410 --> 00:31:26.260
and pretty much
in every country.

00:31:26.260 --> 00:31:31.230
So it seems very strange to
say, somewhere around 1980,

00:31:31.230 --> 00:31:32.910
all these different
countries and all

00:31:32.910 --> 00:31:35.640
these different industries
became less competitive.

00:31:35.640 --> 00:31:37.780
It's much more
natural to say, well,

00:31:37.780 --> 00:31:41.310
in the 1980s we had a
technological shock that

00:31:41.310 --> 00:31:44.400
lowered costs pretty much across
all countries and pretty much

00:31:44.400 --> 00:31:45.690
across all industries.

00:31:45.690 --> 00:31:47.580
It's called the computer.

00:31:47.580 --> 00:31:48.390
Micro-computer.

00:31:48.390 --> 00:31:49.348
That's what we've done.

00:31:49.348 --> 00:31:52.110
And we've seen this
technology work its way

00:31:52.110 --> 00:31:53.970
through with some leaders--

00:31:53.970 --> 00:31:56.670
that is, some companies that are
doing very well because they've

00:31:56.670 --> 00:32:01.140
managed to reduce their costs
and improve their quality

00:32:01.140 --> 00:32:03.085
by using this technology.

00:32:03.085 --> 00:32:04.710
We've seen other
companies that haven't

00:32:04.710 --> 00:32:06.543
done so well, because
they haven't done this

00:32:06.543 --> 00:32:07.810
to the same extent.

00:32:07.810 --> 00:32:12.210
So to me, the technological
hit that reduces marginal cost

00:32:12.210 --> 00:32:15.210
is much more plausible
than the concentration

00:32:15.210 --> 00:32:16.614
hit which increases prices.

00:32:16.614 --> 00:32:18.030
GLEN WEYL: And
what I would say is

00:32:18.030 --> 00:32:21.060
that we had those marginal
costs falling before for reasons

00:32:21.060 --> 00:32:23.670
that were, in fact, more
powerful than the computer.

00:32:23.670 --> 00:32:26.910
Air conditioning,
refrigeration, lots

00:32:26.910 --> 00:32:28.620
of huge technological advances.

00:32:28.620 --> 00:32:30.840
Except at that time,
we had policy makers

00:32:30.840 --> 00:32:33.540
who were innovating, coming up
with things like the welfare

00:32:33.540 --> 00:32:39.090
state, and antitrust
policies, and labor unions,

00:32:39.090 --> 00:32:41.790
that were keeping
up with technology.

00:32:41.790 --> 00:32:44.880
And in the 1980s,
we stopped trying

00:32:44.880 --> 00:32:48.060
to keep up with the
innovations in social policy

00:32:48.060 --> 00:32:50.370
that were necessary to
restrain market power

00:32:50.370 --> 00:32:52.410
within the technology sector.

00:32:52.410 --> 00:32:57.480
And that's the reason why we
suddenly saw those prices not

00:32:57.480 --> 00:33:01.260
track as far down with marginal
costs as they should have done,

00:33:01.260 --> 00:33:05.830
to maintain both maximum
productivity growth and--

00:33:05.830 --> 00:33:07.715
so that's--

00:33:07.715 --> 00:33:09.090
HAL VARIAN: But
the real debate--

00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:13.110
the real question, I think
is, is this just difficult

00:33:13.110 --> 00:33:15.750
to learn how to use and
adopt this technology?

00:33:15.750 --> 00:33:18.240
When electricity came in, we
saw the same thing happen.

00:33:18.240 --> 00:33:20.349
When steam came in,
we saw the same thing.

00:33:20.349 --> 00:33:22.140
It just takes time for
this to work its way

00:33:22.140 --> 00:33:23.515
through the systems,
so you would

00:33:23.515 --> 00:33:26.220
expect some companies are
going to be more productive

00:33:26.220 --> 00:33:27.720
than others, because
they've learned

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:28.920
to master the technology.

00:33:28.920 --> 00:33:31.430
And two of those companies
are represented right here,

00:33:31.430 --> 00:33:33.480
Microsoft and Google.

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:36.540
All right, that's
my debate, and I'm

00:33:36.540 --> 00:33:40.020
sure you've got some more
ready questions coming.

00:33:40.020 --> 00:33:41.047
Why don't we start here.

00:33:41.047 --> 00:33:41.880
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:33:41.880 --> 00:33:45.210
Thank you so much for coming
to speak, and thank you

00:33:45.210 --> 00:33:48.840
for hosting and providing
a lively discussion.

00:33:48.840 --> 00:33:50.550
My name's Stephen.

00:33:50.550 --> 00:33:53.940
I have one question for you
on a subject that you actually

00:33:53.940 --> 00:33:57.660
haven't really touched on yet,
which is the quadratic voting

00:33:57.660 --> 00:33:58.820
piece.

00:33:58.820 --> 00:34:01.770
Simply because I
think politics is sort

00:34:01.770 --> 00:34:04.850
of the iceberg to all of this.

00:34:04.850 --> 00:34:08.090
It's the underlying set of
problems to all of this.

00:34:08.090 --> 00:34:10.530
And so I'm curious,
one, how does

00:34:10.530 --> 00:34:14.250
that actually work, in terms of
how does one define the value

00:34:14.250 --> 00:34:15.510
that each person is given?

00:34:15.510 --> 00:34:19.050
Is it a static equal
value, or can you

00:34:19.050 --> 00:34:22.230
buy more if you
have more income?

00:34:22.230 --> 00:34:26.130
And two, if you're willing
to extend the conversation,

00:34:26.130 --> 00:34:29.070
just how do you think the
globalization of finance

00:34:29.070 --> 00:34:35.340
has impacted this decoupling
of productivity and wages

00:34:35.340 --> 00:34:38.760
that has happened over the past
30 years, which has greatly

00:34:38.760 --> 00:34:42.270
contributed to rising inequality
and many of the problems

00:34:42.270 --> 00:34:46.650
that you're discussing
and thinking about today?

00:34:46.650 --> 00:34:51.040
GLEN WEYL: On the first
point it would be not static.

00:34:51.040 --> 00:34:52.379
It would be dynamic over time.

00:34:52.379 --> 00:34:53.670
People would get voice credits.

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:55.794
They would get a flow of
voice credits the same way

00:34:55.794 --> 00:34:58.414
that they get a flow
of a social dividend.

00:34:58.414 --> 00:35:00.330
But it would be equal
across all people there.

00:35:00.330 --> 00:35:03.330
Would be no opportunity to use
outside financial resources

00:35:03.330 --> 00:35:04.670
to purchase more.

00:35:04.670 --> 00:35:08.400
Unless in some much
more advanced society

00:35:08.400 --> 00:35:10.920
when some of these other
ideas have been implemented

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:13.590
we have much greater
equality in which case

00:35:13.590 --> 00:35:16.430
we might consider allowing
people at least at some rate

00:35:16.430 --> 00:35:19.010
to purchase more credits.

00:35:19.010 --> 00:35:21.560
In terms of the globalization
of finance, look,

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:25.310
I'm not 100% critical of what
happened with neoliberalism.

00:35:25.310 --> 00:35:27.470
I think that there's been
a huge amount of growth

00:35:27.470 --> 00:35:29.840
in the developing world,
and to a large extent, that

00:35:29.840 --> 00:35:33.290
is attributable to the opening
up of the international system

00:35:33.290 --> 00:35:36.060
to allow opportunities
to many more people.

00:35:36.060 --> 00:35:41.790
Unfortunately, while we opened
up to other parts of the world,

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:44.330
I think our economy
domestically,

00:35:44.330 --> 00:35:46.910
within the United States and
within other wealthy countries,

00:35:46.910 --> 00:35:51.440
allowed in this greater market
power and, to some extent,

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:53.660
the external markets
were used as a wedge

00:35:53.660 --> 00:35:55.670
to consolidate the
power of capital

00:35:55.670 --> 00:35:57.660
within national boundaries.

00:35:57.660 --> 00:36:00.780
And so I think we
need to rectify that,

00:36:00.780 --> 00:36:03.500
because otherwise we're going
to get a populist backlash that

00:36:03.500 --> 00:36:06.380
reacts to the fact that
things got better abroad

00:36:06.380 --> 00:36:08.630
and they didn't get
so much better here,

00:36:08.630 --> 00:36:11.180
and that feels
like something that

00:36:11.180 --> 00:36:13.160
can be cured by xenophobia.

00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:17.880
Which it can't, really, but you
see how people get that logic.

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:20.240
So we need to find a
better way to unite

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:22.490
the interests of people
within the country

00:36:22.490 --> 00:36:23.980
and around the world.

00:36:27.034 --> 00:36:28.700
AUDIENCE: What do you
think we can learn

00:36:28.700 --> 00:36:31.910
from the political failures of
the followers of Henry George

00:36:31.910 --> 00:36:34.880
and so on, insofar as
the land value tax,

00:36:34.880 --> 00:36:38.270
the optimal policy they
were proposing at the time,

00:36:38.270 --> 00:36:42.020
largely ran aground in the
Lloyd George budget in UK?

00:36:42.020 --> 00:36:45.780
The House of Lords largely said,
this endangers our interests.

00:36:45.780 --> 00:36:48.170
Here in California,
something like Prop 13,

00:36:48.170 --> 00:36:51.350
which is largely the exact
opposite of an allocatively

00:36:51.350 --> 00:36:55.027
efficient policy, is impossible
to get rid of, seemingly.

00:36:55.027 --> 00:36:57.110
What do you think we can
learn from these failures

00:36:57.110 --> 00:36:59.540
for creating better
policy in the future?

00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:02.270
GLEN WEYL: I think a major
problem for Georgism,

00:37:02.270 --> 00:37:05.030
fundamentally, was the failure
of the Chinese Revolution,

00:37:05.030 --> 00:37:07.630
because it ended
up meaning that--

00:37:07.630 --> 00:37:13.400
Sun Yat-sen, who was founder
of the Chinese Revolution,

00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:15.890
basically had the same
relationship to George

00:37:15.890 --> 00:37:18.540
that Lenin had to Marx.

00:37:18.540 --> 00:37:23.310
And the problem was that
Lenin was much more ruthless.

00:37:23.310 --> 00:37:25.910
He managed to-- the
Bolshevik Revolution managed

00:37:25.910 --> 00:37:28.310
to survive and communism
spread, and that

00:37:28.310 --> 00:37:30.740
became the leading
alternative to capitalism.

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:33.620
And so we got stuck
in a discourse

00:37:33.620 --> 00:37:37.850
where everything was about
capitalism versus communism.

00:37:37.850 --> 00:37:41.240
And so I think,
ultimately, if you

00:37:41.240 --> 00:37:44.080
can have a comprehensive
ideology that

00:37:44.080 --> 00:37:47.450
helps people rethink things,
like Milton Friedman did--

00:37:47.450 --> 00:37:49.490
he really changed
the whole discourse--

00:37:49.490 --> 00:37:54.110
I think that we can
have a path where people

00:37:54.110 --> 00:37:55.790
understand and believe in that.

00:37:55.790 --> 00:37:57.380
And I think he came
close in England.

00:37:57.380 --> 00:38:01.520
I think you change a
few things and Georgism

00:38:01.520 --> 00:38:03.510
would have been very
successful in England.

00:38:03.510 --> 00:38:05.600
But I think that the
communist revolution was

00:38:05.600 --> 00:38:10.590
a big part of what stopped it.

