00:39:10.360 --> 00:39:12.920
the use of free market
rhetoric, by saying

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:17.240
that true free markets
require radical reforms,

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:19.310
radical egalitarian
reforms, I think

00:39:19.310 --> 00:39:23.300
we can change the political
dynamic around these things

00:39:23.300 --> 00:39:25.490
significantly.

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:29.660
But second of all, you know,
it comes from young people.

00:39:29.660 --> 00:39:30.980
It comes from students.

00:39:30.980 --> 00:39:33.770
That's where-- that's how
Milton Friedman changed things

00:39:33.770 --> 00:39:36.380
in the direction that
they went in the 1980s.

00:39:36.380 --> 00:39:41.570
"Capitalism and Freedom" sold
terribly among academics,

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:44.240
initially, and it was very
unpopular in the press,

00:39:44.240 --> 00:39:45.950
but students loved it.

00:39:45.950 --> 00:39:50.210
And he had a coherent view,
and it applied to many things,

00:39:50.210 --> 00:39:52.415
and he really changed the
whole political discourse

00:39:52.415 --> 00:39:53.040
in the country.

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:55.370
So I do believe that
in the medium-term,

00:39:55.370 --> 00:39:59.780
ideas clearly exposited
that try to directly connect

00:39:59.780 --> 00:40:03.140
to the public can have a
huge effect on world history.

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:11.330
AUDIENCE: I'm a newbie to
economics and politics.

00:40:11.330 --> 00:40:14.270
Recently, I watched Ray Dalio's
"How the Economy Works in 30

00:40:14.270 --> 00:40:15.230
Minutes."

00:40:15.230 --> 00:40:17.390
He talks about
borrowing and lending,

00:40:17.390 --> 00:40:19.270
and he says because of
that, we have credit.

00:40:19.270 --> 00:40:20.990
And it's human
nature that we tend

00:40:20.990 --> 00:40:26.870
to borrow from the future, which
leads to some economic crises,

00:40:26.870 --> 00:40:27.730
because of cycles.

00:40:27.730 --> 00:40:32.660
So I'm just wondering,
in your ideal market,

00:40:32.660 --> 00:40:34.340
will there be economic crises?

00:40:34.340 --> 00:40:38.330
And if there are, will
there be differences in how

00:40:38.330 --> 00:40:39.731
we address economic crises?

00:40:39.731 --> 00:40:41.730
GLEN WEYL: I think that
that's a great question.

00:40:41.730 --> 00:40:44.146
I can't say that I confidently
predict that there wouldn't

00:40:44.146 --> 00:40:46.694
be crises in the world
that I'm describing,

00:40:46.694 --> 00:40:48.860
but I think that they would
probably be less severe.

00:40:48.860 --> 00:40:50.568
And the reason is
precisely what you just

00:40:50.568 --> 00:40:55.750
said, which is that debt,
and the rigidities associated

00:40:55.750 --> 00:41:00.410
with private property as well,
are a leading cause of what

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:03.260
happens during economic crises.

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:06.380
And In this world, there
would be far, far less debt,

00:41:06.380 --> 00:41:09.020
because it would be much
less important to take

00:41:09.020 --> 00:41:12.380
on debt to own assets, because
the value of all assets

00:41:12.380 --> 00:41:13.580
would be greatly reduced.

00:41:13.580 --> 00:41:16.910
People would be effectively
closer to renting assets,

00:41:16.910 --> 00:41:19.610
and therefore many of the
sources of instability

00:41:19.610 --> 00:41:24.880
that come from debt finance
would be much less severe.

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:26.390
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:41:26.390 --> 00:41:33.710
My question is, it seems to me
like perhaps some products are

00:41:33.710 --> 00:41:39.680
not naturally amenable to
constant liquid exchange.

00:41:39.680 --> 00:41:41.550
Like housing, for example.

00:41:41.550 --> 00:41:43.910
I might want to live in a
particular place for decades

00:41:43.910 --> 00:41:45.420
at a time.

00:41:45.420 --> 00:41:48.230
And if I'm outbid on it,
and I don't want to leave,

00:41:48.230 --> 00:41:50.750
then getting me to do
so requires violence.

00:41:53.300 --> 00:41:58.520
Or, for example, physical
infrastructure, like trains.

00:41:58.520 --> 00:42:00.560
It seems like there
would be an enormous cost

00:42:00.560 --> 00:42:03.500
if the administration
of this infrastructure

00:42:03.500 --> 00:42:05.540
were constantly changing hands.

00:42:05.540 --> 00:42:06.648
So, I mean--

00:42:06.648 --> 00:42:08.606
I think that that gives
you enough to reply to.

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:15.020
GLEN WEYL: Obviously, you
could maintain stability

00:42:15.020 --> 00:42:17.960
in this world by
charging a higher price,

00:42:17.960 --> 00:42:21.080
so that it's harder for someone
to take something from you.

00:42:21.080 --> 00:42:25.670
Now in our present world, as
well, stability is costly.

00:42:25.670 --> 00:42:29.570
Wealthy people, they live
in safe areas that aren't

00:42:29.570 --> 00:42:31.220
hit by natural disasters.

00:42:31.220 --> 00:42:32.540
They own their houses outright.

00:42:32.540 --> 00:42:35.060
They usually don't rent,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:42:35.060 --> 00:42:37.640
So they enjoy much
greater stability.

00:42:37.640 --> 00:42:41.090
The poor, they rent or
they are underwater often

00:42:41.090 --> 00:42:45.290
with their homes, either
figuratively or literally

00:42:45.290 --> 00:42:49.100
sometimes, living in
very dangerous areas.

00:42:49.100 --> 00:42:52.220
And so in this society, just
like in our present society,

00:42:52.220 --> 00:42:54.320
stability is costly.

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:56.120
But the difference
in this society

00:42:56.120 --> 00:42:58.820
is that everyone would
have an equal, or a far

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:02.210
closer to equal, basis to
pay for that stability,

00:43:02.210 --> 00:43:05.150
as they desired it, than
in our present society,

00:43:05.150 --> 00:43:08.330
because you would tax the
wealthy's demand for stability

00:43:08.330 --> 00:43:11.420
at the cost of the opportunity
of the less well off.

00:43:11.420 --> 00:43:14.420
Whereas in our
present society, they

00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:17.360
can enjoy that stability
at no cost to themselves,

00:43:17.360 --> 00:43:20.403
or a much more limited
cost to themselves.

00:43:27.794 --> 00:43:28.960
AUDIENCE: Hi, it's me again.

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:32.110
I have lots of questions.

00:43:32.110 --> 00:43:37.020
So with regard to both
the self-assessed tax

00:43:37.020 --> 00:43:40.980
and the quadratic voting,
I'm sure the answers would

00:43:40.980 --> 00:43:43.860
be slightly different, but
the question and problem

00:43:43.860 --> 00:43:46.410
that I'm posing, I think,
aren't quite the same.

00:43:46.410 --> 00:43:49.410
Which is, how would you
limit collusion and sort

00:43:49.410 --> 00:43:53.310
of gaming of such a system,
in which individuals could,

00:43:53.310 --> 00:43:57.570
on the self-assess tax side,
more or less set a price that

00:43:57.570 --> 00:43:59.730
is above market, that
others could buy,

00:43:59.730 --> 00:44:02.910
but low enough to
maintain a lower tax?

00:44:02.910 --> 00:44:04.380
And then on the political side--

00:44:04.380 --> 00:44:05.970
this happens in our
elections already,

00:44:05.970 --> 00:44:09.300
people running spoiler
candidates in primaries,

00:44:09.300 --> 00:44:11.370
or having some sort
of spoiler referendum

00:44:11.370 --> 00:44:13.381
to try and split a vote.

00:44:13.381 --> 00:44:15.630
How would you imagine that
could be protected against,

00:44:15.630 --> 00:44:19.140
particularly when, if I were
to put my energy in one issue,

00:44:19.140 --> 00:44:22.350
I would necessarily
be putting less energy

00:44:22.350 --> 00:44:25.550
and voice into another?

00:44:25.550 --> 00:44:27.300
GLEN WEYL: It's more
than I have time for,

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:31.860
to go into detail about
each one of the points,

00:44:31.860 --> 00:44:34.960
in terms of collusion
and so forth.

00:44:34.960 --> 00:44:37.160
But that's an absolutely
central thing to the book.

00:44:37.160 --> 00:44:40.830
I definitely encourage
you to read the book.

00:44:40.830 --> 00:44:44.280
But the short version is,
all those sorts of problems

00:44:44.280 --> 00:44:46.530
exist in our present system.

00:44:46.530 --> 00:44:49.644
They are dramatically
reduced, if not eliminated,

00:44:49.644 --> 00:44:51.060
in the system that
I'm describing.

00:44:51.060 --> 00:44:52.920
I'll just give you one example.

00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:55.560
Right now, there's
the problem, when

00:44:55.560 --> 00:44:58.680
you have an election, of a
spoiler candidate running

00:44:58.680 --> 00:45:02.530
and possibly messing up
the main two candidates.

00:45:02.530 --> 00:45:04.376
But maybe even worse,
there's the fact

00:45:04.376 --> 00:45:06.000
that you can end up
with two candidates

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:09.896
that everyone despises,
but everyone votes for one

00:45:09.896 --> 00:45:11.520
candidate to block
the other candidate.

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:14.072
That's, I think, an even worse
problem than the spoiler.

00:45:14.072 --> 00:45:16.530
In this system, you can show
that that's not mathematically

00:45:16.530 --> 00:45:18.210
possible, because
what happens is

00:45:18.210 --> 00:45:21.120
that, because of the
quadratic nature of the cost,

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:23.100
if you really hate
Hillary Clinton,

00:45:23.100 --> 00:45:25.860
you'll vote at least as much
against Hillary as you'll

00:45:25.860 --> 00:45:29.020
vote in favor of
Trump, and vice versa.

00:45:29.020 --> 00:45:30.540
And so that pushes
two candidates

00:45:30.540 --> 00:45:33.660
that everyone hates
down to zero votes.

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:36.510
And so then that leads
other candidates to rise up,

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:40.710
so you don't end up with these
perverse strategic things,

00:45:40.710 --> 00:45:42.210
where the two leading
candidates get

00:45:42.210 --> 00:45:43.940
reinforced just to
beat the other one.

00:45:43.940 --> 00:45:45.990
AUDIENCE: I'm sorry,
could you repeat that?

00:45:45.990 --> 00:45:48.140
I don't--

00:45:48.140 --> 00:45:50.880
GLEN WEYL: So if you have
two candidates, both of whom

00:45:50.880 --> 00:45:52.440
are really hated
by the other side,

00:45:52.440 --> 00:45:55.830
but no one really likes
them, then what happens

00:45:55.830 --> 00:45:58.470
is that those candidates
get negative votes on them.

00:45:58.470 --> 00:46:01.260
So they go down
to zero net votes.

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:04.560
And so anyone else
who is not despised

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:06.480
ends up becoming a
leading candidate.

00:46:06.480 --> 00:46:09.900
And so you can prove that
that will lead to it never

00:46:09.900 --> 00:46:12.900
being the case that you just
get a perverse thing of two

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:15.834
people that are really
disliked winning just

00:46:15.834 --> 00:46:16.750
to beat the other one.

00:46:19.312 --> 00:46:20.020
Yeah, back there.

00:46:20.020 --> 00:46:23.027
You were waiting.

00:46:23.027 --> 00:46:25.360
AUDIENCE: How do you think
blockchain technology relates

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:29.470
to the ideas in your book
or the research you've done?

00:46:29.470 --> 00:46:31.150
GLEN WEYL: That's a
wonderful question.

00:46:31.150 --> 00:46:34.990
Vitalik Buterin, who is
the founder of Ethereum,

00:46:34.990 --> 00:46:38.624
just wrote a wonderful long
post about that, which I would

00:46:38.624 --> 00:46:39.790
definitely recommend to you.

00:46:39.790 --> 00:46:41.581
And he and I are writing
something together

00:46:41.581 --> 00:46:44.940
that should come out this
week about the relationship.

00:46:44.940 --> 00:46:46.840
But very briefly,
what I would say

00:46:46.840 --> 00:46:50.290
is, the exact technological
relationship is complex

00:46:50.290 --> 00:46:51.530
and it will evolve.

00:46:51.530 --> 00:46:54.550
But philosophically, I think
they're very closely connected.

00:46:54.550 --> 00:46:58.480
In particular, both are
trying to figure out

00:46:58.480 --> 00:47:01.930
monetary, market
based, distributed,

00:47:01.930 --> 00:47:06.520
decentralized systems for
ensuring through rules

00:47:06.520 --> 00:47:10.310
of the game, rather than
through discretionary authority,

00:47:10.310 --> 00:47:16.240
that we have a more egalitarian
distribution of economic power.

00:47:16.240 --> 00:47:18.610
I think a major
weakness in blockchain

00:47:18.610 --> 00:47:21.820
thus far has been that
it's focused primarily

00:47:21.820 --> 00:47:23.830
on the cryptographic
protocols, rather

00:47:23.830 --> 00:47:25.780
than on the substantive
rules implemented

00:47:25.780 --> 00:47:28.280
by those cryptographic
protocols, and as a result,

00:47:28.280 --> 00:47:30.430
some of the rules have
ended up giving power,

00:47:30.430 --> 00:47:33.550
in fact, to oligarchic
groups, say, in China,

00:47:33.550 --> 00:47:35.020
that end up controlling them.

00:47:35.020 --> 00:47:37.603
So they don't really achieve the
goals that they're aiming at.

00:47:37.603 --> 00:47:39.490
What they need is a
substantive set of rules,

00:47:39.490 --> 00:47:42.100
to be implemented by those
cryptographic protocols,

00:47:42.100 --> 00:47:44.680
so that they actually
instantiate their goals.

00:47:44.680 --> 00:47:46.210
And that's precisely
what Buterin

00:47:46.210 --> 00:47:48.340
tries to argue in this
piece, and that we're

00:47:48.340 --> 00:47:49.610
arguing together.

00:47:49.610 --> 00:47:53.670
So I think that there's a tight
unity of purpose between these,

00:47:53.670 --> 00:47:56.890
though the actual technological
connection is something that's

00:47:56.890 --> 00:48:01.390
going to need to develop in the
coming years, or months even.

00:48:01.390 --> 00:48:03.640
I'm actually speaking at
the main Ethereum conference

00:48:03.640 --> 00:48:05.200
on Saturday about exactly this.

00:48:07.770 --> 00:48:08.410
Go ahead.

00:48:08.410 --> 00:48:11.940
AUDIENCE: Just going back
to the previous question.

00:48:11.940 --> 00:48:13.570
To be honest, I
think trying to apply

00:48:13.570 --> 00:48:17.482
any rigorous mathematical
proof to the political system,

00:48:17.482 --> 00:48:19.190
especially the American
political system,

00:48:19.190 --> 00:48:20.820
is doomed to failure.

00:48:20.820 --> 00:48:23.620
But I think one
question I would have,

00:48:23.620 --> 00:48:26.290
in terms of implementation,
you mentioned

00:48:26.290 --> 00:48:31.510
that this quadratic voting
system seems extremely radical.

00:48:31.510 --> 00:48:33.644
What are the sort of baby
steps that you mentioned,

00:48:33.644 --> 00:48:35.560
in terms of actually
trying to implement this,

00:48:35.560 --> 00:48:36.550
especially in the US?

00:48:36.550 --> 00:48:39.255
GLEN WEYL: Absolutely.

00:48:39.255 --> 00:48:40.630
We don't have the
computer going,

00:48:40.630 --> 00:48:42.190
but I can show you afterwards.

00:48:42.190 --> 00:48:45.777
We have a nice user
interface, that

00:48:45.777 --> 00:48:47.860
even for people who haven't
completed high school,

00:48:47.860 --> 00:48:50.740
makes it very intuitive
to do quadratic voting.

00:48:50.740 --> 00:48:52.812
And we've been using
that to do polling,

00:48:52.812 --> 00:48:55.020
and we've gotten some very
interesting results, where

00:48:55.020 --> 00:48:56.980
we were able to elicit
intensity of preference

00:48:56.980 --> 00:49:00.550
much more reliably than you
can get from existing methods.

00:49:00.550 --> 00:49:02.090
That's a good place to start.

00:49:02.090 --> 00:49:04.450
But the next place that
we really want to go

00:49:04.450 --> 00:49:12.069
is ratings, say, of ride-sharing
drivers or products online,

00:49:12.069 --> 00:49:14.110
where you have this problem
of people often going

00:49:14.110 --> 00:49:20.140
to extremes and a lot of sort
of trolling-type behavior.

00:49:20.140 --> 00:49:22.049
And if you made
something costly,

00:49:22.049 --> 00:49:24.590
and made there be real tradeoffs
for people that would budget

00:49:24.590 --> 00:49:26.530
to upvote or downvote
things, I think

00:49:26.530 --> 00:49:30.540
you could get much more
reliable and useful feedback

00:49:30.540 --> 00:49:31.930
In a variety of circumstances.

00:49:31.930 --> 00:49:34.540
AUDIENCE: But in terms of
actually putting into place

00:49:34.540 --> 00:49:36.567
in American elections--

00:49:36.567 --> 00:49:38.650
GLEN WEYL: My view is that
once you start using it

00:49:38.650 --> 00:49:39.910
in some of these
commercial domains,

00:49:39.910 --> 00:49:41.500
you gradually expand
them outwards.

00:49:41.500 --> 00:49:43.630
As people get more used to
it in different domains,

00:49:43.630 --> 00:49:45.088
there will be a
greater willingness

00:49:45.088 --> 00:49:47.746
to experiment in other domains.

00:49:47.746 --> 00:49:49.120
Blockchain is
another place where

00:49:49.120 --> 00:49:51.328
I think that it's quite
likely that this will be used

00:49:51.328 --> 00:49:54.130
in some reasonably near term.

00:49:54.130 --> 00:49:57.160
And I think people will get
used to the technology-- it's

00:49:57.160 --> 00:50:01.720
sort of like, e-government
happened to a large extent

00:50:01.720 --> 00:50:04.570
because of all the
advances that were made

00:50:04.570 --> 00:50:06.852
in the private sector, and
then those were imported

00:50:06.852 --> 00:50:07.810
into the public sector.

00:50:07.810 --> 00:50:10.860
So I expect something similar
would happen with this.

00:50:10.860 --> 00:50:14.514
HAL VARIAN: We'll take
one more question.

00:50:14.514 --> 00:50:15.180
You had the mic?

00:50:15.180 --> 00:50:17.290
Go ahead.

00:50:17.290 --> 00:50:20.692
AUDIENCE: Thank you for
sharing your ideas again.

00:50:20.692 --> 00:50:22.150
I look forward to
reading the book.

00:50:24.800 --> 00:50:29.170
You said that the primary
urgency of what you propose

00:50:29.170 --> 00:50:33.490
is because there is
an impending doom,

00:50:33.490 --> 00:50:37.180
almost, if we don't do something
about the current status quo.

00:50:37.180 --> 00:50:42.970
But do you see this
Marketopia being implemented

00:50:42.970 --> 00:50:44.666
without massive upheaval?

00:50:44.666 --> 00:50:46.540
Because I think what
you're trying to suggest

00:50:46.540 --> 00:50:49.150
is that we need to save
our society, almost.

00:50:49.150 --> 00:50:53.290
But from the way I see it,
it seems like we almost

00:50:53.290 --> 00:50:56.830
need to almost throw
away society in order

00:50:56.830 --> 00:51:00.610
to implement this
without the oligarchs,

00:51:00.610 --> 00:51:03.490
without the current
special interests,

00:51:03.490 --> 00:51:08.140
basically taking control of
this or skewing in a way that,

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:14.800
basically, either ruins it or
prevents it from ever seeing

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:17.930
the light of day.

00:51:17.930 --> 00:51:20.010
GLEN WEYL: I believe
that revolutions

00:51:20.010 --> 00:51:22.560
are not always,
but almost always,

00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:24.630
more destructive than
they are productive.

00:51:24.630 --> 00:51:26.250
And on the other
hand, I do believe

00:51:26.250 --> 00:51:28.680
in the power of
democracy and ideas,

00:51:28.680 --> 00:51:32.130
if widely disseminated,
thoughtfully engaged

00:51:32.130 --> 00:51:36.090
with, and widely understood.

00:51:36.090 --> 00:51:38.790
I think public understanding
is the greatest accountability

00:51:38.790 --> 00:51:41.790
against special
interest capture.

00:51:41.790 --> 00:51:46.110
So I put my faith
in that, ultimately,

00:51:46.110 --> 00:51:49.020
and I hope that young
people, including

00:51:49.020 --> 00:51:51.900
some people in this
room, will build

00:51:51.900 --> 00:51:55.650
on the transmission of different
aspects of these ideas,

00:51:55.650 --> 00:51:59.200
so that we can keep the
broad public engaged

00:51:59.200 --> 00:52:04.530
and keep the political
process accountable to that.

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:08.610
I think you saw with what
happened in the last year

00:52:08.610 --> 00:52:11.146
or two, how much desire
there is for change,

00:52:11.146 --> 00:52:13.020
and if that's channeled
in a direction that's

00:52:13.020 --> 00:52:15.030
productive rather
than destructive,

00:52:15.030 --> 00:52:16.710
I think that we
have an opportunity

00:52:16.710 --> 00:52:21.300
to build a much better society,
like Franklin Delano Roosevelt,

00:52:21.300 --> 00:52:25.660
I believe, did, rather
than just having

00:52:25.660 --> 00:52:28.730
upheaval, a violent upheaval.

00:52:28.730 --> 00:52:31.700
HAL VARIAN: OK, thank
you very much, Glen.

